description.value: Limestone offering-table of A[mu]n...: the shape of this offering-table is based on the form of the alter ideogram, the base of which represents the area for the reception of offerings, while the 'loaf' on top forms the spout. The offering area, which is depressed below the surface of the rim, is covered with representations of offerings carved in shallow sunk relief. The upper surface of the rim bears incised texts invoking funerary offerings on behalf of the workman A[mu]n-... whose full name is lost; in the right-hand text Osiris is invoked and in the left-hand text Horakhty-Atum is named. To the right and left of the 'loaf' are cut the names of Bw-?n t.f and the lady of the house, Nbw-m-ws?t who are presumably husband and wife. The lower left-hand edge and most of the bottom edge have been lost, and the right-hand edge is chipped in places. The losses have been restored in modern times. There are no traces of colour.

description.value:
Fragmentary limestone offering table, broken from a statuette.

The top of the table features carved representations of food, while on the bottom of the table at the left side are partial remains of a sculpted hand. Four fingers are heavily chipped and the thumb is now lost. A ridged section of stone on the opposite end of this surface may indicate a base that the table was once supported with. Around the sides of the offering table, on the left side and front edge, are horizontal lines of incised text. The left side has clear traces of blue paint but much of the text has been erased. This line also contained at least two royal cartouches. The inscription across the front edge is mostly intact and there are traces of a yellow colour within the hieroglyph signs. The two remaining edges of the table are too broken and no text has survived.
